<br>
That's a pretty blanket statement.  I think it goes a little too far.  <br>
<br>
Part of the game should be creativity.  The game designers may put in new_mob_1 with the intention that you need to kill it a certain way.  If people use the skills given to them to find another way .. a way not intended by the game designers .. to kill new_mob_1, that isn't cheating.  It's creativity.  It's using their intelligence.<br>
<br>
As to tradeskills, though, I would tend to agree.  And if you took out the word &quot;especially&quot;, I might agree with the whole thing.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub27.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=seani>Seani</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:orange;'>Tavern Resident</span></span><br>  Posts: 534<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(3/13/03 3:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3159.topic&index=83>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: wow</span><hr size=1> Carpal Tunnel syndrom sure as @#%$ would slow a tradeskiller down, now wouldn't it? =)  RSI/tiredness definitely slowed me down whenever I tried.  <br>
<br>
It's not nice to accuse VI of desiring to inflict physical pain on their customers.  That said however, the logistics of the recipies involved and the tools provided (BYOFinger) to execute them make physical pain a very real obstacle given the average player's desire to reduce the other major demand, time.  It seems that the physical, real-world limitations of the user in terms of moving the mouse and clicking hudreds of thousands of times is a very important means for them to ensure that the skill does, in fact, require a long time to master.  (Though the other, and more effective means used to acomplish the same goal is to make the ingredients only found on mob corpses.)<br>
<br>
A macro program which can move and click your mouse many times faster than is humanly possible is an obvious end-run around the obstacles placed in the player's path to higher achievement.  Macroquest isnt a mind-reading mouse driver that merely eliminates your arms and fingers from the equation.<br>
<br>
The only way you can win the argument is to try and show that the intent of the designers was that tradeskill advancement is meant to be something other than expensive, time consuming, and painful for the player.  Either that or make a case that Macroquest or similar programs are sanctioned by the designers.<br>
<br>
