<br>
Yes the macros would be complicated, though if what was said about &quot;querying the curser&quot; is true, that saves a sh!tload of &quot;ok think, how do I have to lay this out&quot; time and effort.<br>
<br>
Yes, there are cases (mainly with non stacking ingreedients) where you'd have to do the whole bag by hand once to get the macro to go right.  But at the high end of things, you are getting a skill up once every 40-60 combines (on average).  And most recipies are followed for several skill ups.  So, say you use 50 combines per skill up, times, say, 10 skill ups before you go to the next recipie.  Lets just say this recipie takes 30 total actions (clicks moves combines, et all).  Lets also say that this recipie uses 1 non-stacking item.<br>
<br>
By hand: 30 moves x 50 combines x 10 skill ups = 15000 total actions.<br>
<br>
By macro, including setting up the macro for the first time: 30 moves x 10 combines (one bags worth of nonstackables to simplify the macro) = 1 setup macro. 4 macro hits (10 combines each) + (5 macro hits x 9 skill ups) = 300 + 4 + 45 = 349 total actions with more trips to the vender to restock that 1 bag you use for unstackables.  And did I mention you _could_ make a macro that did that too?<br>
<br>
Quite a difference.  Also, all those alternate products?  You could add &quot;error correction&quot; steps to any macro, it'd just increase the complexity (and thats assuming no &quot;cursor querying&quot;)<br>
<br>
As for reasons why macroing is &quot;bad&quot;:<br>
1.  3rd party software.  Like it or not, untill the eula is changed, this is technically wrong.  Weither that stops you, is an entirely different story.<br>
<br>
2.  Allows any old technically advanced person encroach apon the domain previously held by the most dedicated, mostly crazy inner circle of folks (hard core crafters).<br>
<br>
3.  Similar to #2,  Because it takes 90% of the work out of it, making it easy, and removing some of the &quot;martyr ego points&quot; from it.  The person who macros JC is less of a MAN (woman, crafter, whatever) than one who does it &quot;by Hand&quot;, who is less than one who macros thier tailoring batchs of combines (between manually collecting ingredients) who is  less of a MAN than the &quot;by Hand&quot; person.  Hell, Most tailors look down on anyone else, _maybe_ grumblingly admiting that smithing is _almost_ as hard.  &quot;Pfff, JC GM?  Don't they hand that out when you gain lvl X?&quot;<br>
<br>
4.  Macro'ng gets recipies nerfed.  Finding that golden recipie, that actually pays for itself is a grail for which all up and coming crafters lust.  Then those nasty macroers find it, and by producing millions of plat while they sleep, tip off VI that they missed one on thier previous sweeps.  Fish fillets were untouched for _a_long_time_, untill macroing made it big.<br>
<br>
And number 5.  Macros are bad because you didn't use them.<br>
<br>
Edit: garb: The numbers I was seeing were 15 combines A SECOND.  Of course, those folks also painted themselves dayglow orange and waved glowing and blinking flags for the Sony Hitsquad (l33t Ha&gt;&lt;0R division) to snipe.<br>
<br>
