 <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">[61 Warlock] <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=377588">Baron Drakinez Sinminion</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub27.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=quirtevans>QuirtEvans</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:pink;'>Tavern Floor Sweeper</span></span><br>  Posts: 45<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(3/13/03 11:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3159.topic&index=88>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Cheating</span><hr size=1> &quot;it's pretty clear for the most part that VI does in fact have an opinion and a 'vision' for precisely how people should play, overcome obstacles, and win their game. People have quite often been punished, encounters changed, etc when players acted on what you label 'creativity and intelligence'.&quot;<br>
<br>
Too true.  However, you didn't say that VERANT viewed it as cheating, you said that &quot;most players&quot; view it as cheating.  I don't think it's true that &quot;most players&quot; would agree that it's cheating, regardless of what the people at Verant would think.  To me, and I think to many others, part of the fun of the game is finding a different way to solve a particular encounter.  Otherwise, it's just a matter of whether you have enough eye-hand coordination and timing to perform the specific actions Verant intended you to perform.  <br>
<br>
Putting that technical point aside, I've had this argument with the dearly departed Brad McQuaid.  In my view, and I think in the view of many players, anything that is within the coding is fair game, and not cheating.  Verant certainly has the right to change the coding at any time, but if the coding permits a certain action, it's awfully hypocritical of them to say that it's an &quot;exploit&quot; to take advantage of it.  Otherwise, you put the players in the position of being mindreaders .. did the game designer intend to allow me to use this particular bit of coding in this way, or not?  <br>
<br>
Needless to say, Brad didn't agree.  But again, he wasn't &quot;most players&quot;, he was the face of Verant.  His position about exploits was that it was a lot like the Supreme Court's view of pornography .. he knows it when he sees it.  That's because in his mind an exploit was something that the designers didn't intend, and of course he was in a better position than any player to know what the designers intended.  <br>
<br>
Post-Brad, Verant seems to be moving in the direction of fixing the coding, rather than blaming the players.  An example is the &quot;fear pit&quot; that used to exist in PoJ, where all feared mobs would go and get stuck.  They used a rather blunt instrument to fix problem (no more fearing in PoJ), but at least they didn't run around screaming that it was an exploit because everyone knows that feared mobs are supposed to run away and since these mobs couldn't run you were fighting in a way that the designers hadn't intended.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gnashsnobb@thesaryrntavern>Gnash Snobb</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:pink;'>Tavern Floor Sweeper</span></span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(3/23/03 8:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3159.topic&index=89>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> What I always did</span><hr size=1> I had several &quot;tradeskill friends&quot; that I did business with.  What I would do was spend the time rounding up materials that they needed that were rare in exchange for one or two combines I wanted for myself.  Usually to use sometimes to sell.  They knew this and because I got them so many items they needed for tradeskills we had great relationships.  If you don't have plat to pay just barter with tradeskill items....<br>
<br>
Gnash <br>
